06682nam a22007575i 9780773587427DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20122012xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807735874277 a10.1515/97807735874272doi  a(DE-B1597)657278  a(OCoLC)1394872447  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aHT395.C32.O522 2012eb 7aPOL0260002bisacsh04a307.1/2097131 aNelson, Gordon, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aBeyond the Global City :bUnderstanding and Planning for the Diversity of Ontario /cGordon Nelson. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[2012] 4c©2012  a1 online resource (480 p.) :b9 b&w photos  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tThe Origin of Ontario’s Georegions: Pre-European Times to the 1850s -- tThe Industrial Era and the Further Development of Ontario’s Georegions: The Railroads, 1850s–1900s -- tSweetwater Seas and Shores: Waters and Coasts of the Great Lakes Georegion -- tToronto: Putting the Georegion in Perspective -- tThe Carolinian Canada Georegion: Farmland, Forests, and Freeways in Conflict -- tThe Huron Georegion: Rurality in an Urbanizing Province -- tPeterborough: A Georegion in Transition? -- tGeorgian Bay, Muskoka, and Haliburton: More Than Cottage Country? -- tThe Kingston Georegion: Going “Glocal” In a Globalizing World -- tThe Ottawa Valley Georegion -- tLearning from the Past, Assessing the Future: A Geo-historical Overview of Northeastern Ontario -- tNorthwestern Ontario and the Lakehead Georegion: A Region Apart? -- tThe Intersection of Landscape, Legislation, and Local Perceptions in Constructing the Niagara Escarpment as a Distinct Georegion -- tThe Changing Natural Heritage of Ontario in Broad Perspective -- tChanging Cultural Landscapes of Ontario -- tRetrospect and Prospect -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aPolicies promoting Toronto as a global city and provincial economic engine have been seen as beneficial to the development of all of Ontario, yet much of the province has borne significant environmental, social, economic, and political costs as a result of one city's growth. Contributors to this volume call for a radical re-imagining of public policy at local, provincial, and federal levels, that accounts for Ontario's overlooked regions. Beyond the Global City presents a kaleidoscopic view of the province - the rich fields and small towns of the southwest, the productive agricultural lands of rural Huron County, historic Kingston and the Upper St Lawrence, the social and cultural diversity of the Ottawa valley, the near mythical woodlands and waters of Muskoka and Georgian Bay, and the heavily exploited coasts and waters of the Great Lakes - to provide a deeper understanding of its various communities. In a series of regional studies, contributors describe each area's distinctive qualities and challenges and offer recommendations about what is needed to move them forward in a more equitable and sustainable way. Two initial historical chapters lay the framework for the regional discussions, while cross-cutting and integrated chapters analyze the state of natural and cultural heritage and current development theory provincially, offering guidance for the future.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aOntario -- Geography. 0aRegional planning -- Ontario. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Public Policy / Regional Planning.2bisacsh1 aBain, Alison, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCaldwell, Wayne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHilts, Stewart, econtributor